@@eThe Saltglass Reach -- Trade Syndic Jurisdictional Study@@N

The @@yTrade Syndics@@N maintain the Saltglass Reach file not as a route
assessment but as a @@Wlegal curriculum@@N. The Reach is the most
sophisticated jurisdictional gradient on the continent, and every
Syndic apprentice studies its mechanisms before receiving a seal.

The Reach transitions between inland desert and eastern sea -- a
@@ylegal gradient@@N where charter law gives way to maritime risk law
across four terrain bands. The @@WMirror Flats@@N of dead river salt.
The @@rGlasswind Belts@@N of catastrophe-fused silica. The @@yTariff
Cairn Lines@@N of ruined jurisdiction. And the @@eTidemouth Dunes@@N
approaching Mafdet's port.

What commands Syndic attention is the @@yShoreward Conversion@@N: the
formal process translating cargo, contracts, and obligations from
inland desert law to maritime law. Water-debt discharged by pouring
measured volume onto basalt. Cargo owners speaking formulaic oaths
transferring liability from road to sea. @@WShoreward Assessors@@N
bridging both traditions through conversion charts that became
Mafdet's Saltweight standard.

This is precisely the kind of practical jurisdiction transfer the
Syndics study for Roc Road governance. Where Midgaard's eastern half
operates on oath-law and Kiess's western half on convoy-compact law,
the transition at the @@rCrossroads@@N relies on convention. The
Shoreward Conversion proves that a @@yformal mechanism@@N for translating
between legal systems is commercially superior to ambiguity.

The @@yTariff Cairn Lines@@N -- three parallel routes for different cargo
classes -- mirror our own convoy tiering along Roc Road. The Swift
Line for light high-value goods, the Heavy Road for bulk, the Sealed
Route for sensitive consignments. Trade routes under pressure
converge on similar solutions.

The @@gReach Wardens@@N and @@dGlasswalk Guides@@N remind our marshals what
honest route maintenance and strict neutrality look like. The
@@rSynod Whisper Cells@@N using the Glasswind Belts as smuggling
corridors prove that broken terrain and legal ambiguity always
produce exploitation. The same lesson applies at our Crossroads.

The Reach's deepest lesson is inscribed on every surface: salt from
the dead river, glass from the catastrophe, cairns from a collapsed
legal order. @@yEvery landscape carries the fingerprint of institutions
that tried to govern the ungovernable.@@N Kiess reads that inscription
and asks: which of our own fingerprints will the next generation
study as ruin?
